† “Nunquam fallentis termes olivae. ’' The olive crop is still as fickle as the English hop crop—-one good year for two bad ones is the accredited average. The olive crop, like the hop, was and still is often ruinous, from the speculative gambling which its uncertainty tends to stimulate. Horace says that which came home to every olive-grower when he speaks of an olive-tree that never deceived its cultivator.
